6132ec92889c0ce747ae9f7e44f90514: I mean the next one being HTML6 or HTML5.1 or whatever 6132ec92889c0ce747ae9f7e44f90514: in other words, I think <datagrid> is not right as it until recently was specified, and there is no time left to redesign it in the HTML5 cycle, but I'd like to see the feature come back in better form in a later version of HTML I think there's two cases: 1) anything that we want to be parsed in the same way that an unknown element is parsed in HTML5 will work fine 2) anything that needs to be parsed differently, we need to do everything we can to verify that content doesn't depend on the behavior when treated as an unknown element 6132ec92889c0ce747ae9f7e44f90514: I did, and I expect you were making a point, but I did not get what the point was (likely my lack of imagination) I don't follow the logic.. are you saying this behavior for unknown elements would not ever be acceptable for a real element? (in the face of unclosed tags, may I add) I believe what's happening is that <zetagrid> is never closed, due to the lack of a close tag for <p> indeed, so datagrid doesn' t parse the same as an unknown element <span> parses the same as an unknown element (IIRC) 6132ec92889c0ce747ae9f7e44f90514: if I replace zetagrid in your example with span, the parse tree is the same 6132ec92889c0ce747ae9f7e44f90514: if I replace span with zetagrid in your second example, the parse tree is the same yes, some elements are supposed to have <p>-closing behavior that <span> and random unknown elements do not "websock" is a silly name FOR A URI SCHEME

we just change the parsing rules sure, you have to do it carefully it's exactly like the html4-5 transition the rules were nailed down for html4 too, it just wasn't written anywhere 6132ec92889c0ce747ae9f7e44f90514: not anywhere near as wide as you might think a whole bunch of elements in html5 parse like unknown elements according to the HTML5 parsing rules f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: you were phished! f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: i just removed all the checks for whether the text api is supported f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: (since i'd added code that relied on the text api without testing if it was supported, and it was easier to just take out all the checks than try to add more checks in) surely everyone supports the text apis by now i don't have an old copy handy i don't really see the problem with ws: and wss:, but i haven't yet looked closely at the thread

wow, ARIA Role is worse than I thought. It's a band-aid solution written from an ivory tower, seemingly without seriously considering any authoring issues. (I'm fairly sure I'll get flamed for saying that, but oh well) I reached my conclusion from reading the spec I know, but there are IRC log readers who might want the answer anyway BTW, wairole:grid is also addressed by <datagrid> unfortunately, we can't rely on javascript toolkits (or any other tools) saving authors from the complexity 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, are they somewhere in the whatwg.org/issues/ list? when checked, they submit name=value.  when unchecked, they submit nothing I'm not sure mixed state checkboxes should be submitted, since they're usually representative of a group of other checkboxes, and so their state can be determined by examining the state of the others indeed. AFAIK, there is no way for a user to explicity set an individual checkbox to a mixed state in any UI I've seen. the other alternative would be to introduce an attribute <input type=checkbox name=x value="foo" mixed="bar">, where x=foo is submitted in the normal case and x=bar for the mixed case 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884, are you or someone else from apple ever going to get around to providing details about placeholder=""? I recall that you once said someone would do so ok I think most of placeholder is fairly obvious, but in case there's some not-so-obvious detail about it one thing about tristate checkbox that would need to be addressed is that typically, when checking one, the states of the related group of checkboxes is usually toggled too. 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884, is the forms task force ever going to get started? hmm. there are 10 emails pending user approval for public-forms-tf. I can't see what they are though, I don't have permission for that. Maybe they're trying to send but can't? yeah, unless "pending user approval" means that they haven't yet agreed to the W3C's email archive policy, which needs to be done before posts will go through on any list yeah, he has, I just checked, so that can't be the reason thanks d3ca5dde60f88db606021eeba2499c02 do they get automatically purged after a while?

actually, I do think some sort of tagging system for accessibility roles is useful, if only because web applications will want to get ahead of what browsers support natively but I think ARIA Role is not a very good approach to doing that f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: I was being needlessly sarcastic there I agree with you, based also on reading the spec although I think the intent is partly that JavaScript toolkit libraries will do all the heavy lifting, so the scope of authoring issues would be limited tristate checkboxes? how do normal checkboxes submit? the third (indeterminate/mixed) state of tristate checkboxes is mainly useful as an initial state when a group has mixed state and can be toggled on and off as a whole mixed-state checkboxes mainly seem useful for cases where check/uncheck will be handled by script what (if anything) they submit can't just be left unspecified but it's possible that not submitting (just like an unchecked one) might be workable maybe not though I'm probably going to suggest form features for HTML5 that aren't part of WF2 at some point but I don't know if tristate would be high on the list f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: I will remind the relevant person when she gets back from vacation but I'm not sure there's a whole lot to say about it <input type="search"> is probably something that will actually need revision to be spec-worthy, and explication of current behavior I don't think there is anything non-obvious about placeholder it might be possible to come up with a nice solution for that in the context of datagrid at least I think there's definitely controls that would be more useful than some of the half-dozen different date controls in WF2 but I will save it until the current forms stuff is integrated into the main spec (presumably after the Forms Task Force finishes deciding what it is supposed to do and then doing it) f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: we're waiting on the sixth person to give a sign of life f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: there was some rumor that he might be on vacation though I must admit so far it is the slowest-acting six-person group I have ever seen I would assume that shouldn't happen for people who are on the list Sebastian has been an XForms WG member for some time (and I think maybe also XHTML2 WG) I'd be surprised if he hasn't sent any email

mumbles something about having been saying that for years as far as i can tell, there isn't anything in wairole that isn't catered for by html5 (i used the wairole spec as a checklist a year ago or so and made sure) oh right, tristate checkboxes were on the list for wf2 but got bumped to wf3 because i couldn't work out how to submit them neatly lachy: they're probably in the big comment at the bottom of wf2's source what lachy said there's an easy solution (have a second name for the mixed state) but i don't really like that 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884: yeah but you still have to distinguish between left-in-initial-state and unchecked vs checked possible well we'll see wf3 is a far future thing and demand for tristate is low f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: yeah i suggested that easy solution above :-) placeholder will be done before wf3 i'm sure

Hi.  I wanted to ask some questions about WebSockets.  Specifically, how to implement the best server. Does it make more sense to try to get Apache+PHP/Tomcat or something to "hand off" the socket to the ws server (is that even possible?) or just build a second server to put the ws server on? The basic use case is to allow information to be echoed from clients back to clients on the same server as a web server. The clients would be using WebSocket from html5. mod_proxy_fdpass looked interesting, but I'm not sure how well that would work. Ya, I know about socket.io, but that doesn't solve the problem with having the WebSocket server on the same machine as the Web Server.

689fd77594a22590072a42d17c5488ae: PHP doesn't do sockets natively 689fd77594a22590072a42d17c5488ae: and doesn't support long running processes 689fd77594a22590072a42d17c5488ae: so try some alternative 689fd77594a22590072a42d17c5488ae: what kind of server you are building? for what kind of use case? 689fd77594a22590072a42d17c5488ae: this is popular nowadays http://socket.io/#home

cdbe0e8aea85495cfcf22db2db988e7d: I am really not sure who the community is that wants a version of the spec with fewer bugfixes in than the current version I think the stable/editor's draft model is designed around an idea of spec development that doesn't really match reality, at least for the way HTML5 is developed That is, if you have stable versions, N, N+1, etc. and unstable drafts at all times t, it only makes sense to promote version N if, on averge, version N is closer to version N+1 than unstable version at time t(N)<t<t(N+1) cdbe0e8aea85495cfcf22db2db988e7d: It is possible to be unstable, but to be convering on a stable point Heh, putting <plaintext> in <table> so it gets foster parented is amusing a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: tinfb

They are concerned about the accessibility of textbooks in Japan and want to have electronic formats provided in addition to braille and large text. Currently discussing ruby text. One of their requirements is to allow ruby text on both sides of the base text discussing some of the proposals that have come up to hack this into HTML5 markup studying fallback behavior of HTML5 ruby vs XHTML1.1 ruby People here seem to think the fallback behavior of HTML5 ruby is really weird for mono ruby. is not sure whether this should be solved at the HTML level or the style level Murakami-san shows some examples of ruby text, and shows that doing a search in the page does not give useful results since the ruby breaks up the base text, breaking find capability Firefox ruby extension does not have this problem as severely it groups bases belonging to the same ruby but can't find across ruby boundaries Another comment is for footnote markers, which are displayed similar to ruby in Japanese text. (They can be hacked with abspos, but this won't behave correctly at the start/end of a line.) (In my experience, they behave very much like ruby above an empty base, with overhang allowed.) s/mono ruby/jukugo ruby/ fiddles with IE Hm, it supports mono, jukugo, and group ruby. HTML5 seems to assume there is a single bitmap that's part of the canvas state, but I think that's incompatible with efficient WebGL implementations OpenGL doesn't draw onto bitmaps in system memory, unless you manually copy it back from the video card (which is pretty slow) I think that's kind of what's happening with some Direct2D browser experiments, but that's Windows-only and it's apparently really hard if you just have the raw 3D APIs b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: I don't recall coming to any conclusion before, sadly It would be nice to have one at some point before it gets shipped too much wonders if b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea has missed the trend for electronic miniaturisation over the past half a century b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: Things like PSPs and iPhones seem to do decent 3D quite happily, with similar capabilities to full-size consoles from ten years ago and I assume they must cope with the power and heat requirements adequately and I don't see any reason for the trend to stop b5934067b4c7d9c30299478a245d4491: So they could run Half Life 2? :-) I probably shouldn't have said "capabilities" - it seems like they support much more modern features and APIs, but performance is further behind so you have to use the capabilities more sparingly (I know basically nothing about this area though, so mostly I'm just guessing :-) ) At least they don't have to bother with HD resolution output That sounds more like ninth HD, unless you cheat and consider lower-than-standard-cheap-laptop-display to be HD :-) They should call it "middling definition", perhaps 1080p is 1920x1080, hence the "1080" in the name, unless I'm horribly confused (and 1280x720 is 720p) guesses it must have been a marketing person who decided an acronym containing the word "high" was appropriate for sub-VGA resolutions :-p

"When you're using the API, it's always through an existing user in Campfire. There's no special API user. So when you use the API as "david", you get to see and work with what "david" is allowed to. Authenticating is done with an authentication token, which you'll find on the "Edit my Campfire account" screen in Campfire (click the "Reveal authentication token for API" link). When using the authentication token, you don't need a separate password. But since Campfire uses HTTP Basic Authentication, and lots of implementations assume that you want to have a password, it's often easier just to pass in a dummy password, like X." I think this is pretty representative

Quick question: In C, do variable names and function names live in separate namespaces?  (Unrelated to current namespace-related discussion. ^_^) Hrm.  So I can't have a function named "add" and a variable named "add"? Damns, I thought they were separate.  Kk. How does that not cause problems?  ::boggles:: e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: If a user clicks on a link with @ping, the UA will do a normal navigation to whatever the @href is, but it will *also* fire off GET requests to all the urls in @ping. ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: Well, you basically have a big set of global variables you have to manage, and be careful not to shadow. Because then you can't go "add(add,3)" ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: Maybe the C-likes don't have the same problems with names that Lisps do.  We name a lot of functions with words that also are useful as argument names. Like the word "list", which shadows the "list" function in Scheme.  (In CL it doens't shadow, because they live in different namespaces.) e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: If "node" means what I assume it does, then yes? It's meant to allow you to, frex, track how often a particular link is clicked. Lexical, you mean.  C-likes *do* use dynamic scoping.  ^_^ e0563cc2e83070e74ce7019226dd654d: Yes. ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: No, you've got it wrong way round.  Lexical scoping is what allows closures - you resolve free variables based on what's present at the time the function is defined.  Dynamic means you resolve based on what's present at call-time. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scope_(programming) Rather, not at the time the function is defined, but simply at what's present in the surrounding text where the free variable occurs. In C: int x = 0; int f() { return x; } int g() { int x = 1; return f(); } What does g() return? I could have *sworn* C-likes used dynamic scoping.  Guess I'm misremembering my high-school days. In any case, CL and Scheme are both lexical-scope languages, except for their special variables. It doesn't need dictionary lookups to implement dynamic scope.  You just keep a stack around for each binding, pushing and popping as you move between scopes. Man, what is *up* with that foldoc article.  I *assure* you that "(setf x 0) (defun f () x) (defun g () (let ((x 1)) (f))) (g)" returns 0.  Emacs-lisp is a dynamic-scope language, and a number of early lisps were as well, but *all* modern lisps are lexical. Common Lisp and anything created after it. Wow, no wonder.  CL was a new guy at that point. Jeezus. So in conclusion: I had it the right way round, I was just misremembering my C. wouldn't most content model violation bugs then be low priority? now there's a marginally good argument against using style="" (though it applies equally to <style scoped> and even <style>, no?) that seems about as good a reason for warning as it would be to warn on onclick because you can't have more than one handler set that way, and additional ones get slightly different behavior (scope chain, etc) i.e. not completely bogus, but if it were a compiler I'd probably turn that warning off and if we're talking mandatory vs. optional diagnostics, then it might be better to leave it up to individual validators to decide what warnings they emit in addition to errors, and compete on usefulness and quality of those much as C compilers all give basically the same syntax errors, but compete on usefulness of optional warnings (I suspect gcc has far more useful warnings than it would if they were all defined by the C standard) it wouldn't hurt for the spec to editorially suggest some things as possible optional diagnostics I should get going (btw some people might find a warning on use of inline event handler attributes actually useful) (since it's not uncommon to ban them as a house style for a particular site)

http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/public-html/2010May/0095.html "Once you've done all that, you are going to be looking at something very similar to TTML" seems to not have turned out to be true (websrt does all but 1 of his bullet points, if i'm not mistaken) (actually 2, but the second is something we could add pretty easily) i don't understand why <mark> would even remotely be appropriate there, but maybe i'm lacking imagination... what argument would you use to defend it? :-) 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: sure 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: "highlighted for reference purposes" seems a bit of a stretch since your default style is to hide it :-) 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: yeah we have several options here 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: that is, several somewhat orthogonal axes. Rely on or be completely independent from the IRI/URI specs; and define things declaratively or imperatively, being two main ones. 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: i think we're best off doing an independent imperative-style spec for this. 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: maybe with a (normative) appendix that defines the semantics in terms of an IRI 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: the uri spec doesn't define parsing 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: but assuming you mean something the uri spec thinks is valid, then no, because the whole problem is that there are invalid uris we need to handle that have no valid mapping. 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: i basically see no value in defining things the way the spec used to have it, or the way [webaddresses] had it, where the implementor has to do some work to pass the string to some other function to do more work 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: i think we're better off just defining the parsing once and being done with it 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: (we can mostly defer to iri/uri for validity definitions, though) 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: re the annoying thing, i think our best bet is to have hard-coded definitions of the special behaviour for the important schemes, and require generic handling of all the remaining schemes 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: there are three, i think - parsing, resolving, and canonicalisation/serialisation the "authority-style" thing is mostly gone in the more recent specs, iirc yeah iirc the new uri specs have something generic to say about that, i forget what exactly anyway my point is i think we can draw a line in the sand and make it Just Work in the future for future schemes, at least for unknown ones and define what's known not sure what to do about ports we should check what the official specs say since they claim to be knowledge-agnostic nowadays iirc 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: personally all i need is something to reference for the two red boxes in http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/complete.html#urls 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: ideally also we'd get a slightly less mathematical definition of "absolute url" 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: yeah, we might just be stuck with the knowledge thing 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: @datetime? 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: you mean <ins datetime="">? 8b7a8196348038c107614af0b08f2d21: yeah that's pretty special 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: the point of <time> is two-fold, (1) to make it easier to import times into a calendar, e.g. via microdata, and (2) make styling locale-specific 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: neither of these makes much sense for years

Let me know if we want to change those Daniel: Can we schedule a walk on the Riviera for Sunday? We don't seem to have a very full agenda this time. Peter: Let's see how the agenda shapes up Topic: Media Queries Peter: David sent an email about commas being an error handling point David: The basic question is whether errors that are not inside an expression but are between commas cause only the stuff between commas to be ignored or the entire query list to be ignored David: Given the way error handling inside a query, this makes sense. David: But Acid3 assumes the whole query is invalid David: Which means we have several implementations that dot aht. David: I wanted to check that we should change our implementations Anne: I agree this makes sense. Anne: The way Hixie has fixed Acid3 is by commenting out the test, so it wouldn't affect passing Anne: Of course implementations would still have to change their behavior Anne: Opera is willing to change Peter: I assume Mozilla is willing to change. Microsoft? Anne: Microsoft doesn't have an implementation Peter: Any other issues? Anne: That's the only outstanding issue Melinda: Does WebKit have an implementation? Anne: Yes. I don't remember if Hyatt agreed with this change or not. Peter: I'm not hearing any opposition. Seems like a good idea to me. RESOLVED: No change to draft, accept commas as error-handling points. Anne: So, do we publish a Last Call draft now? 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: Yes, let's. Can we publish it before TPAC? Anne: I can try Peter: We'd still need to extend the Last Call period so people have time to publish s/publish/comment/ RESOLVED: Publish Media Queries as Last Call, deadline for comments 4 weeks after TPAC Topic: Test Suite Harness Peter: We had an internal meeting on the test suite harness at HP. Peter: Don't know how long we can have people working on it, so wanted to get comments. Melinda: It would be cool if everybody could give it a 1/2 hour spin Peter: Biggest thing is need to work on reporting functionality http://wiki.csswg.org/test/harness 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: hmm.. the prototype seems to be very out of date Melinda, Peter: We'll send out a url when the latest and greatest is available 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: We redid the templates 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: Also added ability to add a mode to the UA string: whether you are testing desktop screen, or projection mode, or print or print preview 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: so those can each get a different set of results Topic: Page Break of Floats Melinda: I wanted to revisit Issue 74 Melinda: http://wiki.csswg.org/spec/css2.1#issue-74 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: I agree with adding "Avoid breaking inside a replaced element" 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: I'm not convinced about the other part 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: I'm concerned about breaking web layouts 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: which rely on floats and tables Melinda: This whole section is fuzzily worded anyway Melinda: we want implementations to think about what they're doing and do the best they can Melinda: At some point we may evolve more rigorous rules here. Howcome: I think i agree that more rigorous rules would be useful, but at this point I don't know what they would be Peter: where do we go from here? 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: Does anyone object to adding "Avoid breaking inside a replaced element"? RESOLVED: Add "Avoid breaking inside a replaced element" for Issue 74 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: I'm not terribly excited about the other stuff. Hi Karl, what brings you to the wild webapps west? Yes, I am. I had a teleconf with the Mobile Web Test Suites WG and we decided on editorial changes that needed to be made to the P&C to make it testable I guess minutes from the teleconf must be available in the MWTS archives. You may recall, this was also the agreement that we had with Dom as part of his Last Call comments. The changes include... Artb, not yet (as I have not checked in the changes). But I will. Great Karl! then I can ask you QA questions :) Artb, I was saying, the changes are... amen to that! 1. identify the class of product through markup to which an assertion applies (e.g.,  A <span class="product-ua">user agent</span> <em class="ct">must</em> ) 2. Put a stable IDs on every testable assertion (e.g, <p id="123123"> <span class="product-ua">user agent</span> <em class="ct">must</em> ) 3. Remove untestable assertions that's pretty much it So, then Dom will extend his Testable Assertion extractor to build test tables. f47636673b14c54021a69dc06f6a19fb, we have one already! It's neat :) We just want to extend it to group by product. gets url http://www.w3.org/2005/08/online_xslt/xslt?xslfile=http%3A%2F%2Fdev.w3.org%2F2006%2Fwaf%2Fwidgets%2Ftests%2FextractTestAssertions.xsl&xmlfile=http%3A%2F%2Fcgi.w3.org%2Fcgi-bin%2Ftidy-if%3FdocAddr%3Dhttp%253A%252F%252Fwww.w3.org%252FTR%252Fwidgets%252F 4dd217ba7542bb00a127f682e2c3ad27: the aim is to get a stable version to test against yes, 9bb295af93051e68de66b2bd517b2e24, then we can link to them from here:  http://dev.w3.org/2006/waf/widgets/tests/plan.html 4dd217ba7542bb00a127f682e2c3ad27: at the moment, yes. But the aim is to kill those and make the text descriptive (or change the text to make it testable). Hendry, it's on my todo. Right after I finish fixing the spec so we can test it. Artb: and example of an assertion that is wrong "A language tag is a text string that must match the production of a Language-Tag defined in the [BCP47] specifications." Anne2, must needs to be dropped as the above defines "language tag". The user agent tests if a language tag is valid in another part of the spec. The language tag cannot test itself. trying to follow what Danc sez in http://www.w3.org/2001/01/mp23 s/trying to follow/trying to apply Artb, thoughts? It certainly can. It will make testing much easier. 4dd217ba7542bb00a127f682e2c3ad27: I agree. No such changes will be made.

Hmm, can a ZFS filesystem have different mountpoints in different zones? Just checking... my brain is trying to shut down for the night, so things are a bit fuzzy. :) What I'm looking to do is have a ZFS filesystem that contains directories to hold my (and my users) mp3s... from the global zone, my desktop, I'll have complete control, but from the zone where my users will log in I only need to have them able to add files into their own directories, and for a third zone I want the filesystem read-only. *nods* That's what I seem to be gathering from the docs, though Sun's information on this is a bit vague at points. It mentions that the filesystem needs its mountpoint set to legacy, but doesn't say if that's necessary in the global zone or just the non-global zones... http://docs.sun.com/app/docs/doc/817-2271/6mhupg6gj?a=view in particular is being confusing. What differences will that create? I will give that a shot tomorrow... thanks for the help, gramload. er, gramlord (Definitely need sleep... *sigh*)

Any directory, be it a plain directory or a ufs file system or a zfs file system or whatever, can be placed within any zone's file system space at any point by using the 'add fs' config option. So two zones can see different directories (to them) that are in fact the same directory on the global zone. If you are referring to giving a zfs file system to two different zones via the dataset option then I doubt that Solaris will allow it.  Haven't tried it, but doubt that it will work. I'm guessing that you'll need something like 'add fs; dir=(local zone directory); special=(global directory where mp3's reside); type=lofs' on the zone where they are allowed to add mp3's, and a similar one but somehow specify that it's read-only for your third zone. The "mountpoint set to legacy" I take as meaning a zfs dataset that added to a zone, not a plain old directory. Do a typy=lofs rather then type=zfs. type It's not exporting the zfs dataset, just a loopback mount point to a directory. ... which happens to be a zfs file system, but that shouldn't matter. MindDrive, in case you are still in the land of the waking, I just tried creating such a zfs f/s on the global zone and add fs as type=lofs into a zone and it worked fine.
